The pageant ends with the most beautiful of all its figures. Virgil, in describing the hero of these last six books, had already ventured a touch of the supernatural; here he indulges his imagination still more strongly.1 Camilla, who bears a name that should awake the national spirit in every Italian‚2 and prepare him for an idealised heroine, is re- vealed more fully in the eleventh book, where the wonderful story of her infancy is told; but in these few lines her portrait is already perfect, without a flaw in thought or expression.
